    <div class="sec-t">About</div>
    <p>Stegastein is a <strong>cantilevered viewing platform</strong> projecting 30 metres out from the mountainside on County Road Fv.5627, 650 metres above the Aurlandsfjord in Aurland municipality, Vestland county. It was designed by architects <strong>Todd Saunders and Tommie Wilhelmsen</strong> and completed in 2006 as part of the Norwegian Scenic Routes (Nasjonale turistveger) Aurlandsfjellet programme — one of 18 designated scenic roads in Norway combining road infrastructure with commissioned architecture and installations.</p>
    <p>The platform is constructed of <strong>steel clad with laminated pine wood</strong>, is 3.3 metres wide, and has a glass front panel at its end. It sits on a mountainside above the pine trees and provides an unobstructed view of the Aurlandsfjord, the village of Aurland, and the surrounding mountains. The road over the Aurlandsfjellet from Aurland to Lærdal (47 km total) is <strong>closed in winter from approximately October/November to May/June</strong> due to snow, but the section from Aurlandsvangen to Stegastein itself remains open year-round; the road may close temporarily at night or in severe weather even when nominally open.</p>
    <p>The platform is <strong>free and publicly accessible at all times</strong>, with free parking and wheelchair-accessible facilities. Toilets are available at the platform during the operating season (closed in winter). Guided shuttle bus service from Flåm and Aurland operates throughout the year via norwaysbest.com. The platform is one of the most photographed viewpoints in the Sognefjord region. Any site selling tickets to visit Stegastein is fraudulent — no admission exists. Last updated: March 2026 · Verified</p>
